{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512647","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512647"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:58:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:58:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11935"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11935","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11935"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.59,0.05,0.03,0.28,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4531"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110161"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4531","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4531"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11935"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92459"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"688"},{"type":"tags","id":"1667"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6698"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6707"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6750"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9814"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10270"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11333"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18167"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35846"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42687"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110161","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110161"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to his GP as he is worried that he is going bald. For the past year, he has noticed his hair is thinner and has been drier and more brittle than usual. This has been associated with intermittent constipation, weight gain of 8kg and increasing fatigue. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn clinical examination, his BMI is 29 and the significant findings are cool and dry peripheries and loss of hair on the outer third of the eyebrows. His past medical history includes iron deficiency anaemia, ischaemic heart disease, osteoarthritis and depression for which he is receiving treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn further investigation, his Hb is 130g/L (120-160 g/L), fasting glucose is 6.5mmol/L, TSH is 11mU/L (0.45-4.5), free T4 is 12 (10-20) and TPOAb is elevated at 34 kIU/L. A repeat investigation 3 months later shows a TSH of 12 mU/L and free T4 is 12.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["25-50 mcg levothyroxine PO daily, adjusting every 4-8 weeks","Repeat thyroid function tests in 8-12 weeks","Oral iodine supplementation","1.6 mcg/kg levothyroxine PO daily, adjusting every 4-8 weeks","CT brain"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is presenting with symptoms consistent with hypothyroidism. Even though the serum T4 lies within normal range, given the significant and systemic involvement including dermatological, gastrointestinal, cardiovascular and psychiatric illnesses that may be attributed to hypothyroidism, thyroid replacement therapy must be initiated as soon as possible. Levothyroxine is commonly dosed by weight, (1.6 mcg/kg/day). However, in patients with underlying ischaemic heart disease, initial partial replacement should be used, which is dosed at 25-50 mcg/day. This is because levothyroxine increases myocardial oxygen demand, potentially leading to cardiac arrhythmias, angina pectoris, or myocardial infarction. Therefore, the patient must be monitored regularly of his symptoms and thyroid function every 4-8 weeks, and adjusting the dosage appropriately.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat thyroid function tests\u003C/strong\u003E and ongoing monitoring is a plausible choice if the patient has subclinical hypothyroidism that is asymptomatic. A randomised control trial showed that in patients who have asymptomatic subclinical hypothyroidism, thyroid replacement therapy did not improve clinical outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral iodine supplement \u003C/strong\u003Eis not routinely used in hypothyroidism. Although iodine is a major constituent of thyroid hormones, hypothyroidism is rarely caused by iodine deficiency. In this patient, there are no features from the history that suggests iodine deficiency. Rather, the elevated TPO antibody is suggestive of autoimmune thyroiditis that contributed to the hypothyroidism. Therefore, oral iodine supplementation would not have any effects on the management of this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT brain \u003C/strong\u003Emay be considered if one is concerned about central hypothyroidism, which is more commonly associated with a pituitary adenoma resulting in reduced TSH and subsequent reduced T4. However, this does not match the clinical picture as the patient has elevated TSH and no other signs of hypopituitarism, which is another feature commonly seen in pituitart adenoma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Treat symptomatic subclinical hypothyroidism in non-pregnant adults with levothyroxine of 1.6mcg/kg/day","In patients with a background of ischaemic heart disease, a reduced dosage of levothyroxine is preferred due to the risk associated with cardiovascular side effects"],"references":["InformedHealth.org [Internet]. Cologne, Germany: Institute for Quality and Efficiency in Health Care (IQWiG); 2006-. Underactive thyroid: Deciding whether or not to treat subclinical hypothyroidism. 2014 Oct 8 [Updated 2017 Aug 10]. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK279600","Biondi B, Cappola AR, Cooper DS. Subclinical hypothyroidism: A review. JAMA 2019;322(2):153\u201360. doi: 10.1001/jama.2019.9052.","Management of subclinical hypothyroidism. RACGP. (n.d.). https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/key-racgp-guidelines/view-all-racgp-guidelines/first-do-no-harm/gp-resources/management-of-subclinical-hypothyroidism#:~:text=Subclinical%20hypothyroidism%20is%20a%20biochemical,gain%2C%20constipation%20and%20dry%20skin.","Bekkering GE, Agoritsas T, Lytvyn L, Heen AF, Feller M, Moutzouri E, et al. Thyroid hormones treatment for subclinical hypothyroidism: a clinical practice guideline. BMJ. 2019 May 14;l2006.","Ross DS. Treatment of primary hypothyroidism in adults. In: UpToDate, Connor RF (Ed), Wolters Kluwer. (Accessed on 16 Apr 2024)","Hypothyroidism, Published June 2019. In: Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; accessed 16 Apr 2024. https://www.tg.org.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92459"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11935"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92459","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92459"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-28T19:05:17+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-28T19:05:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4531"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110161"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadi